Non Linear Models

library(ISLR)
attach(Wage)

Polynomials

# fit a 4th degree polynomial model
fit = lm(wage ~ poly(age,degree=4), 
         data=Wage)
summary(fit)

# Plotting is not so straightforward
agelims = range(age)
age.grid=seq(from=agelims[1], to=agelims[2])
length(age.grid)
## [1] 63
preds = predict(fit, newdata=list(age=age.grid),
                se=TRUE)
se.bands = cbind(preds$fit + 2 * preds$se,
                 preds$fit - 2 * preds$se)
length(se.bands)
## [1] 126
plot(age,wage,col="darkgrey")
lines(age.grid,preds$fit,col="blue",lwd=2)
matlines(age.grid,se.bands,col="blue",lty=2)

# another way of fitting

# Nested sequence of models
fita = lm(wage ~ education, data=Wage)
fitb = lm(wage ~ education + age, data=Wage)
fitc = lm(wage ~ education + poly(age, degree=2), data=Wage)
fitd = lm(wage ~ education + poly(age, degree=3), data=Wage)
anova(fita, fitb, fitc, fitd)

Polynomial logistic regression

Binary response is wage > 250K. See band of high wage earners in plot above.

fit = glm(I(wage > 250) ~ poly(age, degree=3), data=Wage,
          family = binomial)
summary(fit)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = I(wage > 250) ~ poly(age, degree = 3), family = binomial, 
##     data = Wage)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -0.2808  -0.2736  -0.2487  -0.1758   3.2868  
## 
## Coefficients:
##                        Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept)             -3.8486     0.1597 -24.100  < 2e-16 ***
## poly(age, degree = 3)1  37.8846    11.4818   3.300 0.000968 ***
## poly(age, degree = 3)2 -29.5129    10.5626  -2.794 0.005205 ** 
## poly(age, degree = 3)3   9.7966     8.9990   1.089 0.276317    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 730.53  on 2999  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 707.92  on 2996  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 715.92
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 8
preds=predict(fit, list(age=age.grid), se=TRUE)
# tricky; add three numbers to fitted values: 0, -2se, +2se
se.bands = preds$fit + cbind(fit = 0, 
                             lower = -2 * preds$se,
                             upper = 2 * preds$se)
head(se.bands)
##         fit      lower     upper
## 1 -7.664756 -10.759826 -4.569686
## 2 -7.324776 -10.106699 -4.542852
## 3 -7.001732  -9.492821 -4.510643
## 4 -6.695229  -8.917158 -4.473300
## 5 -6.404868  -8.378691 -4.431045
## 6 -6.130251  -7.876426 -4.384076
# inverse logit
prob.bands = exp(se.bands) / (1 + exp(se.bands))
matplot(age.grid, prob.bands,
        col="blue", lwd=c(2,1,1), lty=c(1,2,2), type="l",
        ylim=c(0, 0.1))
# add a rug
points(jitter(age),I(wage>250)/10,pch="|,cex=.5")
